,Not Recommended,323670,26408941,"Posted: 3 November, 2016",all,Reed,"Before I say anything, I'd like to make it clear Ididenjoy this game, I just wouldn't reccomend you to buy it.I loved zipping around the track, and I have a soft spot for any game that let's me play as Carol Tea ofFreedom Planet, even if that does make me someone usually avoided at parties. Infact, the whole character set is actually pretty great, and aside from a few visuals, such as the melon-with-a-face (used in-game as a menu cursor among other things), which are awkwardly smooth for a retro-style video game, the graphics are absolutely great. It's deffinitely a fun game to look at.That's where the ""but"" comes in, and this is a big ""but."" It's a lot of fun to look at, but a lot less so to play. That's because this game cannot decide if it wants to be Mario Kart on the SNES or Mario Kart 8; the courses themselves are more like the SNES game, being flat and often very blocky, with only about half of the tracks having any real smooth turns. The turning controls themselves are also very comparible to SNES Mario Kart, being somewhat slidey and slow (though arguably a littletoo slow), but allowing for brisk and speedy turns using a slide. However, while these two design choices work well with each other, they're both made near-unenjoyable by the fact that rather than making the karts move only at a reasonable speed as in the SNES Mario Kart, allowing players to better judge turns and react to the other racers and track hazards without being hindered by the slower turning speeds, the game decides it needs to try to keep the player's attention by making every car go extremely fast. This leads to the problem that due to the slow turning and the quick speeds, by the time you notice an obsticle it's already too late to really avoid it. This, combined with the fact that the blocky track designs often require tight 45 degree turns, means you'll be hitting things a lot.This game has potential, but either they need to slow down the gameplay, or completely redesign the tracks."
