,Not Recommended,323670,28758647,"Posted: 28 December, 2016",all,Schatt3npakt,"[EDIT: 03. 01.2017]Onscreenbuttons for the controller work, although the controller isn't automatically detected, but quite a few controller layouts are supported, for example PS4, SNES or OUYA layouts![ORIGINAL REVIEW]This isn't flatout bad, and I can see why people enoy this. But I have seen better.First of all, while my wired xbox-controller worked fine, the on-screen keycommands were still displayed for the keyboard.  And while it's not rocket science to figure three buttons out, it still holds back the ""pick-up-and-play""-aspect I expect from a kart racer.The gameplay is very similar to the original Mario Kart. You drive, you throw things, you try to win. The controls, in my opinion, feel a bit floaty and lack the grip of similar kart racers, but maybe that's just me.What this game offers is challenge. The tracks are harder than you might expect, with a lot of sharp turns, many jumps, and an abundance of obstacles. And it doesn't help that, when you get hit, your driver AND the camera spins around, leaving you guessing whether you are still looking in the right direction.As for the tons of tracks and crossovers (SO MANY CHARACTERS!), it doesn't add much to the game. Every track and character feels pretty much the same. The idea behind the VR-TRAX, which are maybe 70 % of the tracks in the game, is that they look like tron-style meshes in different colours. I was underwhelmed.There are other aspects I don't like, for example the toned down music, the AI that seems as helpless as I am and so on, but I just wanted something quick, easy and fun to play with friends or alone.But apart from screaming ""LOOK AT ALL THESE INDIE GAME CROSSOVERS"" right in my ear, this doesn't offer much to me."
